{"id": "2026-07-08-science-chiral-superconductivity-in-graphene-gets-a-full", "date": "2026-07-08", "stream": "science", "headline": "Chiral superconductivity in graphene gets a full set of switchable flavours", "summary": "Transport on rhombohedral hexalayer graphene reveals a new chiral superconducting state whose chirality and spin-valley character are switchable by several tuning knobs.", "url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.06520", "source_domain": "arxiv.org", "tier": "T1", "tags": ["preprint"], "topics": ["science"], "importance": 2, "display_body": "Superconductivity in rhombohedral graphene grows out of a magnetic quarter-metal parent state and appears to be chiral: the electron pairs circulate with a built-in handedness that breaks time-reversal symmetry. This transport study on hexalayer graphene reports a new superconducting state and shows its chirality and spin-valley character can be flipped with several independent knobs. Chiral superconductors can in principle host non-Abelian anyons, exotic quasiparticles whose braiding could encode a noise-protected qubit. The result is a control demonstration, not a claim of anyons.", "why": "One of the most-watched candidate platforms for topological quantum computing just became far more controllable in the lab.", "thread_id": "2026-07-08-science-chiral-superconductivity-in-graphene-gets-a-full", "first_seen_date": "2026-07-08", "event_date": "2026-07-07", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": ""}
{"id": "2026-07-08-science-a-clean-proof-that-quantum-proofs-are-more-power", "date": "2026-07-08", "stream": "science", "headline": "A clean proof that quantum proofs are more powerful than classical ones", "summary": "Recent classical-oracle separations show QMA is strictly larger than QCMA; a Quanta explainer this week decodes the result.", "url": "https://www.quantamagazine.org/researchers-reveal-the-power-of-quantum-proofs-20260706/", "source_domain": "quantamagazine.org", "tier": "T2", "tags": ["single-source"], "topics": ["science"], "importance": 2, "display_body": "The question: does it help for a short certificate to be a fragile quantum state rather than an ordinary bit-string? The classes are QMA (verifiable with a quantum proof) and QCMA (classical proof). Recent results separate them by constructing a classical oracle relative to which QMA is provably strictly larger than QCMA. A February paper reaches the same separation more simply using good error-correcting codes. The honest scope: this is a relativized separation, the standard first step toward, but not yet, an unconditional one.", "why": "It pins down in a rigorous setting that quantum information is not just faster to compute with but genuinely more expressive as evidence.", "thread_id": "2026-07-08-science-a-clean-proof-that-quantum-proofs-are-more-power", "first_seen_date": "2026-07-08", "event_date": "2026-07-06", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": ""}
{"id": "2026-07-08-science-a-half-billion-year-old-fossil-traces-where-spid", "date": "2026-07-08", "stream": "science", "headline": "A half-billion-year-old fossil traces where spiders' fangs came from", "summary": "X-ray microtomography of the Cambrian arthropod Urokodia supports chelicerae evolving from megacheiran great appendages and book gills from trunk limbs.", "url": "https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-026-10713-2", "source_domain": "nature.com", "tier": "T1", "tags": [], "topics": ["science"], "importance": 2, "display_body": "Chelicerates are defined by their chelicerae, the pincer/fang appendages at the front of the head, and by book gills. Using X-ray microtomography to reconstruct the 3D anatomy of Urokodia, a Cambrian arthropod, the authors argue the chelicerae evolved from the grasping great appendages of megacheirans and the book gills from their trunk limbs, filling in the morphological transition that intermediate fossils had left unresolved.", "why": "It strengthens a specific, testable story for the deep origin of one of the most successful animal body plans on Earth.", "thread_id": "2026-07-08-science-a-half-billion-year-old-fossil-traces-where-spid", "first_seen_date": "2026-07-08", "event_date": "2026-07-01", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": "", "affiliations": ["Yunnan University, Kunming", "University of Leicester"]}
{"id": "2026-07-08-science-how-a-bacterium-sneaks-inside-its-host-a-clue-to", "date": "2026-07-08", "stream": "science", "headline": "How a bacterium sneaks inside its host, a clue to how symbioses get started", "summary": "Buchnera, the obligate aphid endosymbiont, secretes an effector protein SyeA resembling pathogen effectors and essential for transmission.", "url": "https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-026-10711-4", "source_domain": "nature.com", "tier": "T1", "tags": [], "topics": ["science"], "importance": 1, "display_body": "Buchnera is the obligate endosymbiont of aphids, living permanently inside specialised host cells. The authors identify a previously uncharacterised Buchnera protein, SyeA, secreted into the host cytoplasm, resembling the effectors disease-causing bacteria use to manipulate cells, present in the ancestral Buchnera, and essential for the symbiont's transmission. An ancient intracellular partnership appears to rely on the same molecular toolkit as bacterial pathogenesis.", "why": "It blurs the line between infection and partnership, and hints at how the intracellular symbioses that gave rise to organelles like mitochondria could have first taken hold.", "thread_id": "2026-07-08-science-how-a-bacterium-sneaks-inside-its-host-a-clue-to", "first_seen_date": "2026-07-08", "event_date": "2026-07-01", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": "", "affiliations": ["University of Texas at Austin", "Max Planck Institute for Chemical Ecology, Jena"]}
{"id": "2026-07-08-science-interstellar-comet-3i-atlas-carries-nitrogen-and", "date": "2026-07-08", "stream": "science", "headline": "Interstellar comet 3I/ATLAS carries nitrogen and carbon unlike any Solar System comet", "summary": "VLT/UVES CN spectra give 3I/ATLAS a normal 12C/13C but an anomalously high 14N/15N, the first nitrogen-isotope measurement of an interstellar object, pointing to a cold distant origin.", "url": "https://www.nature.com/articles/s41550-026-02921-7", "source_domain": "nature.com", "tier": "T1", "tags": [], "topics": ["science"], "importance": 3, "display_body": "3I/ATLAS is only the third confirmed interstellar object, after 1I/'Oumuamua and 2I/Borisov. Using the CN molecule in ESO Very Large Telescope spectra, the team measured a carbon ratio 12C/13C = 151 (roughly Solar-System-like) but a nitrogen ratio 14N/15N about 363, much higher than the ~150 typical of Solar System comets. Because these ratios are set by formation temperature and radiation, the anomalous nitrogen points to a cold, distant birthplace. It is the first nitrogen-isotope measurement for any interstellar object and extends an earlier July study that found 3I/ATLAS's water is extremely deuterium-rich.", "why": "Interstellar objects are our only direct physical samples of other planetary systems, and 3I/ATLAS keeps refusing to look like anything from our own.", "thread_id": "2026-07-08-science-interstellar-comet-3i-atlas-carries-nitrogen-and", "first_seen_date": "2026-07-08", "event_date": "2026-07-06", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": ""}
{"id": "2026-07-08-science-quaoar-s-shape-and-density-nailed-down-by-14-yea", "date": "2026-07-08", "stream": "science", "headline": "Quaoar's shape and density, nailed down by 14 years of stars blinking out", "summary": "28 stellar occultations of trans-Neptunian object Quaoar over 2018-2025 fit an oblate ellipsoid (~1094 km diameter) and confirm no global atmosphere.", "url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.06450", "source_domain": "arxiv.org", "tier": "T1", "tags": ["preprint"], "topics": ["science"], "importance": 1, "display_body": "When a distant body passes in front of a background star, timing that blink from several sites gives its size and shape far more precisely than direct imaging. Combining 28 occultations of the trans-Neptunian object Quaoar from 2018-2025 with nine earlier events, the authors fit an oblate ellipsoid: equatorial radii ~566 km, polar radius ~511 km, equivalent diameter 1094 +/- 5 km, geometric albedo ~0.13. The shape constraint sharpens Quaoar's bulk density and confirms it holds essentially no global atmosphere, notable for a world hosting a ring beyond where theory says rings should survive.", "why": "Precise bulk properties for individual Kuiper-belt worlds are the raw material for testing how the outer Solar System's dwarf planets formed.", "thread_id": "2026-07-08-science-quaoar-s-shape-and-density-nailed-down-by-14-yea", "first_seen_date": "2026-07-08", "event_date": "2026-07-07", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": ""}
